  "prompt": "What are some good psychological thriller movies of 2015?",
  "response": "2015 featured several compelling psychological thrillers that captivated audiences with their intricate plots, intense performances, and suspenseful storytelling. Here are some noteworthy titles from that year:\n\n1. **Gone Girl**\n   - **Director:** David Fincher\n   - **Synopsis:** Based on Gillian Flynn's bestselling novel, this film follows the mysterious disappearance of Amy Dunne (Rosamund Pike) and the ensuing media frenzy that puts her husband, Nick Dunne (Ben Affleck), under intense scrutiny. As secrets unravel, the story delves into themes of deception, media manipulation, and the complexities of marriage.\n\n2. **The Gift**\n   - **Director:** Joel Edgerton\n   - **Synopsis:** This psychological thriller centers on Simon (Jason Bateman) and his wife Robyn (Rebecca Hall), whose lives are shaken when Simon's old high school acquaintance, Gordo (Joel Edgerton), resurfaces with enigmatic gifts and unsettling intentions. The film explores themes of past trauma, obsession, and the ripple effects of long-buried secrets.\n\n3. **Jessica**\n   - **Director:** Steven Soderbergh\n   - **Synopsis:** While more of a crime drama, \"Jessica\" incorporates psychological thriller elements as it tells the story of a suburbia housewife (Annette Bening) who gets entangled in her husband's corrupt business dealings. The tension builds as she navigates deceit, moral dilemmas, and personal transformation.\n\n4. **The Invitation**\n   - **Director:** Karyn Kusama\n   - **Synopsis:** Although technically released in late 2015 in festivals and 2016 in wider release, this film deserves mention. It follows Will (Logan Marshall-Green) as he attends a dinner party hosted by his ex-wife and her new husband. As the evening progresses, unsettling tensions and mysterious motives come to light, creating an atmosphere of paranoia and suspense.\n\n5. **Inherent Vice**\n   - **Director:** Paul Thomas Anderson\n   - **Synopsis:** Based on Thomas Pynchon's novel, this film blends noir and psychological thriller elements as it follows private investigator Doc Sportello (Joaquin Phoenix) navigating a complex web of conspiracies, love interests, and surreal events in 1970s Los Angeles.\n\nThese films offer a range of psychological thrills, from intense character studies and domestic suspense to intricate mysteries and mind-bending narratives. If you enjoyed these, you might also explore other thrillers by the same directors or delve into related genres for more gripping storytelling.",
